I didn't have a look at a lot of the links but at several and I would
like to point out that the links I did check seem to many refer to the
negative consquences (ie confiscation of the weapons and worse) from
Jewish German citizens. This I didn't know about but it certainly fits
the picture of what I knew about that part of German history.

A little bit of Googleing &amp; Wikipediaing in Germany brought up the
following link (yes, it's in German):

http://www1.polizei-nrw.de/moenchengladbach/Waffenrecht/article/Historie
_des_Waffenrechts.html

It's published on the official Police website of the town of
Moenchengladbach and a short history of gun laws in Germany from 1851
onwards.

Feel free to run this through Babelfish or similar but I'll try to
summarize the important points here because they seem to also corborate
what I mentioned:

- It seems that from 1851 onwards, it was illegal to carry a weapon (in
public, I presume) that was hidden inside another object like a cane.
There were no other laws specifically targeting gun ownership.

- At the end of WW I, a lot of German soldiers went home with their
guns and ammo as the German armies hadn't surrendered; some of them got
sold on or just put away into the cupboard. Germany in the 20s had an
extremely volatile political climate so plenty of military weapons in
private hands resulted in armed uprisings, political assassinations and
the whole banana republic way of doing politics. As a consequence, laws
were inacted that banned the public from owning firearms, a ban that
was only revoked in 1928 and replaced with a law that severly
restricted the ownership of handguns - you basically had to prove that
you had a need for owning a handgun before you could get a permit to
buy one. You'd only get a permit for a rifle if you could prove that
you're a hunter (which wasn't and isn't as easy as in the US; normally
you 'rent' the right to hunt in some woods from the owner of said piece
of land with the result that hunting was and is a sport for the rich).

- Interestingly enough, during the Nazi period the gun laws were
actually relaxed inasmuch as you didn't need a permit for buying rifles
from 1938 onwards; you still needed a permit for a handgun though, and
all firearms would have to be registered. They author of the article
actually quotes part of this particular law and the part I find very
interesting is that the law specifically says that its purpose is to
make it easier for citizens to acquire firearms, but at the same time
the police should be able to prevent purchase and ownership of firearms
by those elements of society that were deemed &quot;unreliable&quot; and
potentially &quot;enemies of the state&quot;. And of course those &quot;unreliable&quot;
&quot;enemies of the state&quot; would cover everybody who was to the left of
Ghenghis Khan politically, homosexuals, Sinti &amp; Roma
(gypsies/travellers), anybody you didn't like and ratted out to the
authorities and of course the Jewish population. From what I've scanned
of the pages you mentioned, this is most likely the laws that were used
to confiscate the firearms owned by all those undesirables.

- /All/ ownership of any kind of firearm was banned between 1946 and
1951; from 1952 onwards, a large part of the 1938 law that relaxed the
restrictions of weapons ownership was reinstated. These laws were
finally superceded by more restrictive laws in 1972 and they've been
fiddling with them ever since. To make them more restrictive, of course
- there have been a couple (yes, I think it was one or two) incidents
of school shootings in the past 5-10 years which offered a welcome
excuse to tighten the screws even more.

So it looks like in a sense we were both right...

