Talking *individual* ownership...

NFA of 1934 put a $200 _tax_ on full-auto weapons and also on
silencers, short-barrelled shotguns, short-barrelled rifles and
&quot;destructive devices&quot;.  &quot;Any other weapons&quot; described under the act
are only charged a $5 tax.  The idea was to tax the &quot;assualt weapons&quot;
of the time out of the reach of the normal consumer and have a legal
arguement against their mere possesssion by gangsters because most
would not have paid the tax before they obtained their weapon.
Remember Al Capone?  He was busted for not paying taxes.  The same
approach applies here.

Fast forward to 1986 and the GCA.  The GCA put all legally taxed full
auto weapons into a pool that regular joes could transfer between each
other as long as they can legally possess *any* firearm (your normal
&quot;yellow form&quot;, but now white, 4473 sales) and as long as the proper
paperwork is done and the $200 tax is paid.  Your heir can inherit
your NFA weapon tax free as long as they can legally possess a
firearm.

Regular joes could no longer build their own full auto or convert a
semi to full under the GCA, nor buy post-'86 full auto weapons.  Legal
possession, manufacture and dealing in post-'86 full auto weapons is
currently limited to the government, law enforcement, military,
Special (Occupational) Taxpayers and within limits, holders of the
appropriate FFLs.

